instance virtual_to_physical_interaction : DTDFVocab:VirtualToPhysical [
    base:desc "Control commands issued by the digital twin – such as a desired speed command and an emergency braking command – are encapsulated by the Data Translation component to produce ROS 2 compliant messages which are forwarded over the Wi‑Fi UDP link to the Physical Twin’s Vehicle Control Front‑End. Upon receipt, the Vehicle Control FE validates the command payload against its operational limits before forwarding it to the Motor Actuation and Steering Servo Actuation Front‑Ends, which in turn drive the physical actuators. Confirmation of command execution is provided via updated vehicle state telemetry, which flows back through the same communication channel, enabling the digital twin to confirm the actuation and resolve any conflicts by treating the most recent state feedback as the authoritative value."
]

instance twinning_time_scale : DTDFVocab:TimeScale [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin system synchronizes the time of computation offloading devices using a shared notion of time with an accuracy requirement of 100 ms. This tolerance accommodates the hardware limitation of the participating automotive computing units and meets the safety‑critical vehicular application need for robust time alignment. Although the document does not specify exact synchronization frequencies or granularity beyond this 100 ms window, the design implies a periodic time‑synchronization routine at least as frequent as the ECU update cycle."
]

instance dt_constellation : DTDFVocab:Constellation [
    base:desc "The system follows the ISO 23247 reference architecture but introduces a dedicated Physical Twin Entity to reflect the actual vehicle resources. Software Functional Elements (FE) are mapped to individual ROS 2 packages; each FE is implemented as one or more ROS 2 nodes. Components are grouped into the three entities: user‑centric visualization/control nodes under the User Entity; data‑store and control nodes under the Digital Twin Entity; and sensor‑preprocessing/actuation/communication nodes under the Physical Twin Entity. Inter‑entity communication relies on ROS 2 message passing, allowing decentralized coordination without a central orchestrator. Resource management is implicit in the hardware deployment of the entities, while system‑wide coordination is achieved through ROS 2 topics, services, and action servers."
]

instance dt_technical_connection : DTDFVocab:TechnicalConnection [
    base:desc "The digital twin’s software components communicate internally using ROS 2, which relies on a DDS‑based multicast middleware for low‑latency intra‑component messaging. Inter‑entity communication between the Physical Twin and Digital Twin layers is performed over a Wi‑Fi network employing the UDP transport protocol. The architecture is distributed, with sensors and real‑time data pre‑processing deployed on edge hardware in the vehicle, while higher‑level services such as visualization, reporting, and data storage may be hosted in a cloud or on‑premises environment. The system requires a network latency not to exceed 100 ms between the physical and virtual layers, ensuring timely state updates and control execution. While explicit bandwidth or redundancy specifications are not provided, the architecture must support continuous streaming of high‑volume LiDAR point clouds and low‑weight control messages across the wireless link."
]

instance dt_hosting_deployment : DTDFVocab:Deployment [
    base:desc "Each twin component is deployed on distinct hardware platforms: low‑latency sensor data pre‑processing (LiDAR clustering, data translation) runs on an in‑vehicle edge node, vehicle state collection and actuator control operate on the vehicle’s embedded ECU, while visualization, reporting, and data storage are hosted on a cloud or on‑premise back‑end. This hybrid deployment model allows the system to leverage edge computing for time‑critical data processing and actuation, and cloud resources for scalable data analytics, report generation, and user interface access. The architecture supports scalability by adding additional edge nodes or expanding cloud resources, and offers both on‑premise and cloud deployment options to meet varying reliability, maintenance, and cost requirements."
]

instance standardization : DTDFVocab:Standardization [
    base:desc "The system adheres to ISO 23247 – Digital Twin Framework for Manufacturing, specifically Part 2 (Reference Architecture). The architecture is entity‑based: Observable Manufacturing Element (OME), Data Collection and Device Control Entity, Digital Twin Entity, and User Entity. Each entity comprises Functional Entities that perform tasks such as actuating the OME, transforming data into a human‑interpretable format, or user interface integration. The implementation can use OPC Unified Architecture, as suggested by the standard. The demonstrator is publicly available via the GitHub repository at https://github.com/McSCert/Automotive-Digital-Twin and a YouTube video at https://youtu.be/Rv-sJJQc3WU."
]

instance security_and_safety_considerations : DTDFVocab:SecuritySafety [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin system is engineered in compliance with ISO 26262‑1:2018 Road Vehicles – Functional Safety, ensuring that safety‑integrity levels are defined, risk assessments performed, and safety lifecycle processes are integrated throughout development. Performance requirements for Adaptive Cruise Control are governed by ISO 15622:2018, which specifies test procedures and safety constraints that the Twin must meet. Service‑level constraints for V2X communication are derived from 3GPP TS 22.185, which defines latency and quality‑of‑service targets for safety‑critical vehicle‑to‑everything services. The architecture follows a model‑driven approach as described by Dalibor et al. (2020), enabling systematic verification and validation of the Twin’s interactive cockpit components and supporting traceability of safety‑critical design decisions. "
]
